<H3> <TI>   Congressmen Comment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Congressmen Comment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0604214294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0604214294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast" program] </F>
  [Excerpts] Today the "National Newscast" learned about the 
U.S. State Department's annual report on the struggle against 
drug trafficking. 
  The report places the country in the dock and notes that 
corruption is widespread in Colombia, particularly in the 
judicial branch. [passage omitted ] 
  The policy of surrendering to justice which the State 
Department criticizes has also been a controversial issue in 
Colombia. 
  We consulted congressmen who approved the Penal Procedure 
Code: 
  [Begin recording] [Senator Hernan Echeverri] We politely 
reject this insinuation and this sort of U.S. intervention in 
our domestic affairs. 
  [Representative Ramiro Lucio] The Colombian Congress, 
independently -- without consulting the U.S. State Department, 
the Belgian Justice Ministry, or any other authority any where 
in the world -- decided to approve the Penal Procedure Code 
basically including the antidrug policy that the national 
government presented to us. 
  [Senator Alberto Santofimio Botero] What is happening is 
that we are increasingly losing our sovereignty. We are going 
to wind up asking the gringos what we are to do in order to 
issue laws in Colombia. 
  [Representative Edmundo Guevara] It is easier to see the 
mote in your brother's eye than to see the beam in your own. It 
is in the United States where sentences are negotiated. We 
copied from them. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

