  [Excerpt] Antonio Suarez, president of the National 
Association of Judicial Employees, and Gabriel de Vega, director 
of the National Drug Directorate, commented on the U.S. State 
Department's harsh, controversial report. 
  [Begin recording] [Suarez] We have been criticized for not 
having a strong enough hand, but we have a list of 262 judges 
and employees assassinated in Colombia. We would not have such 
a long history of bloodshed if we weren't doing something. The 
U.S. State Department's remarks are interfering and an attempt 
to meddle in Colombia's administration of justice. That is why 
we, just this once, support the prosecutor general's policy. 
  [De Vega] As far as my office is concerned, the report is 
objective and measured. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

