<H3> <TI>   Mitsubishi Official Interviewed on Marketing Plans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mitsubishi Official Interviewed on Marketing Plans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0704234094 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0704234094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Mitsubishi Corporation recently announced it 
will enter the Cuban market and formalize its presence in Cuba. 
Martin Rodin, president of Mitsubishi Motors in Cuba, was 
interviewed by Mariela Diaz. 
  [Begin recording] [Rodin] We have been working in Cuba for 
almost 14 years. Mitsubishi's decision came after eight months 
of work. This decision encompasses more than importing and 
selling vehicles. Once the decision to enter the Cuban market 
was made, the Japanese sent a work group to Cuba to examine all 
technical aspects involving the vehicles. 
  [Diaz] What types of vehicles will you be marketing? 
  [Rodin] The automobile will be the Lancer. They will be 
used, 
for now, as rental cars for tourism. There is also a great 
demand for diesel engine box vans, minibuses for 12 and 26 
passengers. Following today's or tomorrow's signing of the 
contract with Transimport (as heard), we will begin to import a 
full line of trucks, both medium and heavy load. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

