<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace Commissioner Comments on Recent Agreements </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peace Commissioner Comments on Recent Agreements </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0804000394 Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO in Spanish 5 Apr 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PA0804000394 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 4 April, Peace Commission leader Hector Rosada 
Granados reported that both the uprooting of people by the local 
armed confrontation and the historic clarification of the past 
-- known as the Truth Commission's work -- will be treated 
separately by the government and guerrilla delegates in May in 
what will be a follow-up of the peace talks. Rosada Granados 
said these subjects will be discussed in this order and that the 
second one will be debated in an ad hoc meeting. He said 
special mechanisms will be used to complete the discussion after 
it was decided to carry out the study and analysis. The official 
said the signing of the framework agreement early in the year 
was the end of the beginning and that the General Agreement on 
Human Rights now marks the beginning of the end. 
  Rosada said he regards the fulfillment of the agreement very 
probable because he detected in the URNG [Guatemalan National 
Revolutionary Unity] commanders a determination to make good 
their words and reach a political understanding so they can be 
reincorporated into the country's legal life. He said the URNG 
leaders have also pledged their word abroad, and the negotiators 
and the international community are waiting for the two sides to 
abide by the agreement. Finally, he said the only thing that 
remains is to march forward with common sense and tolerance so 
this process, which now exists only on paper, can become reality. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

