<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister: U.S. Official's Comments `Vague' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister: U.S. Official's Comments `Vague' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0704164894 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 7 
Apr 94 p 40 </F>

<F P=103> PA0704164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esteban Huertas G.] </F>
  [Text] "The statements by Robert Gelbard, U.S. deputy 
assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs, are 
vague and ambiguous when he says Panama is a drug 
money-laundering center," Foreign Minister Jose Raul Mulino said 
yesterday. Mulino said: "Gelbard's statements are not specific 
and shed no light on the faults committed by Panamanian 
authorities." 
  The foreign minister said that "the administration's report 
does not give names and places where the illegalities occur." 
Mulino said: "The case to which the document alluded was the 
raid on the Gil Cafe Company, but added there was no sustaining 
evidence in the fact." [sentence as published] 
  For his part, Supreme Court Magistrate Jose Manuel Faundes 
cited "the strange U.S. attitude of discrediting Panama's image 
before the concert of nations." Faundes stressed the national 
authorities' cooperation against drug trafficking, a situation 
that can be brought up in the face of any accusation on the part 
of the United States." [no opening quotation mark as published] 
The magistrate said: "Panamanian international financial centers 
have controlled money laundering, something to which U.S. banks 
can attest." 
  A U.S. delegation is visiting the country and being escorted 
by Olegario Barrelier, president of the National Banking 
Association (ABN). This visit will last until 11 April, 
according to Barrelier's agenda. 

</TEXT>

