<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0804004394 </F>
<F P=103> PY0804004394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 7 April. 
  The increase in interest rates on the U.S. market, and the 
expectations that this rate will continue to grow, has prompted 
foreign investors to withdraw approximately $1 billion from the 
Brazilian stock market in one week. The decision has also 
affected the Brazilian foreign debt, as higher interest will 
make debt certificates more expensive. (Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO 
PAULO in Portuguese 5 Apr 94 Section 2 p 1) 
  The Sao Paulo stock market yesterday registered its sharpest 
drop of the year (10.5 percent), with losses estimated at 
between $12 and $16.5 billion. This drop was prompted by a U.S. 
Federal Reserve decision to increase interest rates. According 
to Citibank, on 29 March the stock market value stood at $132 
billion, a loss of $16.5 billion. Fibra Bank director Julio 
Krauspenhar estimated the loss at $12 billion. (Sao Paulo O 
ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 5 Apr 94 p B3) 
  The Sao Paulo State Federation of Industries, FIESP, and the 
Sao Paulo State Industries Center has reported that the Sao 
Paulo industrial activity level dropped by 1.5 percent in 
February in comparison with January. Industrial activity in 
February has nonetheless increased by 3.6 percent in comparison 
with the same month last year. The use of installed industrial 
capacity climbed from 75.1 percent in January to 75.3 percent in 
February. Meanwhile, real sales of electric-electronic and 
communications materials increased by 65.7 percent, mechanical 
capital goods and agricultural machinery sales increased by 15.2 
percent, car industry sales increased by 11.7 percent, furniture 
sales increased 9.6 percent, and metalworks sales by 9.5 percent 
in January 1994 in comparison with January 1993. In all, sales 
of Sao Paulo industry dropped in February by 0.4 percent in 
comparison with the previous month, which is still 4.6 percent 
more than the sales registered in February 1993. The hours 
worked in February in the industry sector dropped by 1.5 percent 
in comparison with January, and the average real salary 
increased by 3.9 percent, while the salary mass increased by 1.6 
percent on real terms. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in 
Portuguese 31 Mar p 10) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

