<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zedillo Appoints Campaign Manager; Reassures Labor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zedillo Appoints Campaign Manager; Reassures Labor </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0804004394 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0430 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0804004394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] PRI [Institutional Revolutionary Party] deputies, 
senators, and assembly members have affirmed their total support 
for PRI presidential candidate Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon. 
Thanking them for their support, Zedillo said he favored honest 
elections and respect for the citizen's vote. 
  [Begin Zedillo recording] As the PRI's presidential 
candidate, I promise to respect the electoral law reliablely and 
honestly. Today I confirm, before my party colleagues and the 
entire nation, that I will assume each and every one of my 
party's commitments in favor of electoral democracy. [end 
recording] 
  Zedillo reiterated he will not accept any illicit votes and 
demanded that there be an external audit of the electoral 
register. He said he will heed the decisions, reached by 
consensus, on the presence of foreign visitors at the elections. 
  The PRI candidate said he is prepared to debate other 
presidential candidates and added that PRI members do not fear 
democracy. Zedillo observed that lasting economic progress and 
social improvement can only be achieved in a democratic system. 
  At the meeting with the legislators, candidate Zedillo 
appointed new PRI Secretary General Ignacio Pichardo Pagaza as 
the general coordinator of his political campaign. 
  Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon also met with CTM 
[Confederation of Mexican Workers] leaders and promised to 
defend the workers' rights. He said he will allow changes to 
the labor law that will benefit Mexican workers and added that 
their benefits will not be withdrawn. 
  [Begin Zedillo recording] The time has come for wages to 
improve in Mexico. We can do this without risking the stability 
that has cost us so much. We will do it by improving 
productivity and making sure the benefits that result from this 
productivity end up in the Mexican workers' pockets. [end 
recording] 
  As he arrived and when he left the CTM auditorium, the PRI 
candidate hailed all PRI members gathered there. 

</TEXT>

