<H3> <TI>   Daily Denounces Fuel Smuggling </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily Denounces Fuel Smuggling </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0704220094 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0704220094 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] On 6 April, the Dominican newspaper EL DIARIO 
denounced the smuggling of oil products between the Dominican 
Republic and Haiti, which is being done extensively, according 
to the newspaper. A reporter of the daily confirmed that 
transactions between Haitians and Dominicans are made daily in 
homes, located not far from the border between the two 
countries, where the products are stored. The trafficking of 
fuel and other products affected by the international embargo is 
done for the profit of the Haitian military regime, according to 
the Dominican daily. The article points out that in Dajabon, a 
region located 350 km northeast of Santo Domingo, a gallon of 
gasoline is sold for 55 Dominican pesos, that is, $5; whereas 
the regular price is 20 pesos, or $1.50. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

