<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aristide Notes Treaty Expiration; Rejects U.S. Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aristide Notes Treaty Expiration; Rejects U.S. Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0704175494 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1045 
GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0704175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 6 Aprio, President-in-exile Jean-Bertrand 
Aristide denounced in an official letter the agreement signed 
with the United States in 1981 on refugees. He did so to protest 
the systematic return by the United States to Haiti of those who 
want to leave the country. This agreement constitutes the legal 
basis of U.S. Coast Guard efforts to systematically return 
Haitian refugees who attempt to enter the United States. 
  Mr. Michael Barnes added that President-in-exile 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide also gave notice of his refusal of the 
latest plan for a settlement to the crisis in Haiti. U.S. Vice 
President Al Gore presented the plan to the president last 
month. Father Aristide considers unacceptable the American 
proposal to lift the sanctions before his return to Haiti as 
head of state. 
  The American policy is a perversion of democracy, says the 
letter to President Bill Clinton from the Haitian president, who 
has lived in exile since 1991. The letter points out that in 
any case the 1981 convention concerning the refugees expires in 
six months. 
  It should be recalled that the American policy regarding the 
Haitian refugees is based on the presumption that the refugees 
are not fleeing persecution, which is unbelievable, writes 
President Aristide. He reproaches Mr. Bill Clinton for having 
taken on the responsibility for the policy of his Republican 
predecessor George Bush, who began to send back Haitian refugees 
in 1992. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

