<H3> <TI>   University Conducts Illegal Emigration Study </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    University Conducts Illegal Emigration Study </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0904013794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 2300 
GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0904013794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks are recorded] </F>
  [Text] Illegal immigration is an issue on which our people 
have many different views. It is an extremely dangerous endeavor 
for those who have emigrated illegally from Cuba by sea. 
Research is being conducted precisely on this topic by a 
specialist of the Center for Political Alternatives of the 
University of Havana. Its deputy director, Antonio Aja, explains: 
  [Aja] "This is an in-depth study of the characteristics of 
those who emigrate illegally; the motives of the people who make 
the decision to emigrate illegally; who they are; what their 
reasons are; and the risks taken once the decision and attempt 
to illegally emigrate is made." 
  The researcher also spoke about the significance of this act 
for national security and human life. 
  [Aja] "Emigrating through the Guantanamo Naval Base is not 
the same as emigrating in a raft." 
  The classification of people who attempt to emigrate by sea 
was another of the goals of this study. 
  [Aja] "They can basically be classified as young. This is 
understandable because, first of all, this endeavor requires a 
certain physical ability." 
  This interview is only an excerpt of a broad subject that we 
will discuss further in this program over the next few days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

