<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senate Bloc Approves New Presidential Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Senate Bloc Approves New Presidential Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1104031594 Paris AFP in Spanish 0215 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1104031594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 10 Apr (AFP) -- The Haitian Senate 
Bloc, not recognized by the international community, today 
approved a motion for the appointment of a provisional president 
and the calling of elections. The bloc approved the motion by 
11 votes in favor and two opposed thanks to the support of the 
eight senators elected in the January 1993 partial legislative 
elections which has been challenged by the international 
community. 
  The proposals refer to the application of Article 149 of the 
Constitution that foresees the appointment of the president of 
the court of appeals as president of the Republic in case of a 
prolonged absence by the president. The Constitution stipulates 
that in such cases, elections must be called within a "45 to 90 
day" period. 
  The senators decided to announce their decision to the 
Chamber of Deputies and Appeals Court President Emile 
Jonassaint. The deputies had already approved another plan, 
supported by the United States and the United Nations, to solve 
the country's crisis, but not with the senatorial bloc (led by 
Firmin Jean-Louis) acknowledged by the international community. 
  Deposed President Jean Bertrand Aristide rejected the 
aforementioned plan that contemplates the designation of a new 
prime minister after the departure of Army Chief General Raoul 
Cedras, even though no mention is made of the date when he will 
be able to return to the country. [sentence as received] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

