<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dominican Government Said Opposed to UN Border Observers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dominican Government Said Opposed to UN Border Observers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0804234894 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1045 
GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0804234894 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Dominican Republic is opposed to the presence of 
foreign observers on the border between Haiti and the Dominican 
Republic. On 7 April, Dominican Vice Chancellor Fabio Herrera 
Cabral criticized the idea of sending UN observers to the 
Dominican Republic border. Vice Chancellor Fabio Herrera Cabral 
said that to post foreign observers on both sides of the border 
would be an insult to national sovereignty. 
  He added, however, that the Dominican Government would be 
agreeable to accepting observers if they were recruited from 
among the Dominican population. Mr. Fabio Herrera Cabral was 
reacting to statements by a UN spokesman raising the possibility 
of observing the behavior of Dominican authorities from the 
border with Haiti. 
  It should be pointed out that over the past few days the 
Dominican Government was subjected to severe criticism because 
of its ambiguous attitude toward the embargo, especially its 
providing gasoline and gas oil to the Republic of Haiti. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

