<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unofficial Election Results Favor Ruling Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Unofficial Election Results Favor Ruling Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1004225894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2129 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1004225894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 10 Apr (EFE) -- The ruling 
Justicialist Party (Peronist) won in the elections held today to 
choose 305 legislators tasked with reforming the Constitution, 
according to private polls held "by word of mouth." The Great 
Front [Frente Grande] center-left coalition won in the federal 
capital and moved up to third place in Buenos Aires Province, 
the country's most populated district. 
  It is reckoned that President Carlos Menem's Peronism won 
between 43 and 45 percent of the votes in the country's 24 
districts. The Great Front won between 35-36.5 percent of the 
votes in the federal capital, followed by Peronism with 25.5 
percent, and the Radical Civic Union (UCR) with 15 percent, 
according to polls conducted by Buenos Aires television stations. 
  The voting results in the federal capital mean a hard defeat 
for radicalism led by former Argentine President Raul Alfonsin. 
  Menem's Justicialist Party won 44.5 percent of the votes in 
Buenos Aires Province, followed by the UCR with 15.2 percent of 
the votes, the Great Front with 14.7 percent, and the right-wing 
Movement for Dignity and Independence [MODIN] with 11.7 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

