<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Vows Not To Renegotiate Canal Treaties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Vows Not To Renegotiate Canal Treaties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0804164994 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 8 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PA0804164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ibeth Vega G.] </F>
  [Text] President Guillermo Endara said yesterday that under 
no circumstance will he consider renegotiating the 
Torrijos-Carter Treaties to prolong the existence of U.S. 
military bases in Panama beyond the year 2000. 
  Endara's statements followed the arrival of a U.S. mission 
headed by Republican Phil Crane. The U.S. delegation is in 
Panama to collect information from different economic and 
political sectors on the possibility of renegotiating the 
presence of U.S. military bases in Panama. According to the 
Panama Canal treaties, the last U.S. soldier has to leave 
national territory before midnight on 31 December 1999. 
  The U.S. delegation of about 25 people met with President 
Endara yesterday. The delegation also plans to meet with 
different business groups, as well as with the presidential 
candidates for the 8 May elections (Ernesto Perez Balladares, 
Ruben Blades, Mireya Moscoso de Gruber, and Ruben Blades [as 
published]). 
  "They visited me, and I told them I had a promise to fulfill 
for the people--a promise I made in the 1989 campaign, when I 
vowed that during my administration the renegotiation of the 
treaties will not be considered under any circumstance," the 
Panamanian president said. 
  According to Crane, prolonging the presence of U.S. military 
bases along the Panama Canal and in national territory will 
guarantee the security of both countries, as well as the 
security of the entire world. Crane also said Panama would 
benefit economically "because it will simply be a business deal 
between two countries." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

