<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Franco To Separate Economic Plan From Campaign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Franco To Separate Economic Plan From Campaign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0804234694 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 8 
Apr 94 p A4 </F>

<F P=103> PY0804234694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Tania Monteiro] </F>
  [Excerpt] Brasilia -- President Itamar Franco is trying to 
separate the economic plan from the presidential candidacy of 
former Minister Fernando Henrique Cardoso (PSDB) [Brazilian 
Social Democracy Party]. He fears that the stabilization 
program, chosen by the PSDB as its main campaign banner, will be 
rejected in Congress for electoral reasons. His main concern is 
the PMDB [Brazilian Democratic Movement Party], which believes 
the PSDB candidate will be the main beneficiary if inflation is 
curbed. 
  "We need maturity; the stabilization plan is not simply a 
convenient electoral banner, but a national commitment that must 
be complied with, even by future governments, for the benefit of 
the country," Franco said. On 6 April Franco discussed the 
subject during a meeting with Cardoso, Civilian Household 
Minister Henrique Hargreaves, and Deputy Luiz Carlos Santos 
(PMDB-SP) [Sao Paulo], the government leader in the lower house. 
Franco still intends to talk with the government leader in the 
Senate, Pedro Simon (PMDB-RS) [Rio Grande do Sul] and with other 
party leaders. Franco will probably even summon a cabinet 
meeting to explain that the economic plan must not be confused 
with the PSDB candidacy. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

