<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Finance Minister Faces `Same Problems' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Finance Minister Faces `Same Problems' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0804234594 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 8 
Apr 94 p A3 </F>

<F P=103> PY0804234594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial from the "Notes and Information" column: "New </F>
Ministry, Old Problems"] 
  [Excerpts] Provisional Measure [MP] No. 434 is gone, and 
No. 457 has come; and the new finance minister still faces the 
same problems his predecessor had, as Congress still wants to 
modify the MP so as to distort the economic plan. This matter 
was the main subject of analysis during the first workday of 
Finance Minister Rubens Ricupero. In meeting with some of the 
members of the congressional committee that will give an opinion 
on MP 457, Minister Ricupero verified that obstacles still 
exist, and with a further aggravating factor: After the exit of 
Fernando Henrique Cardoso, political interests are still 
hindering the approval of the economic plan. 
  Congress does not consider itself defeated by the executive 
branch triumph in having MP 434 reedited. The electioneering 
congressmen insist on introducing three modifications to the MP: 
a recovery of salary losses, a minimum salary increase, and the 
inclusion of a certain kind of price freeze. The only objective 
of these changes is to make the economic plan not feasible. 
[passage omitted] 
  The problem is that the new finance minister does not have 
Cardoso's ability to convince the congressmen to approve the 
economic plan. The fact that Cardoso is a candidate for 
president of the Republic has increased the number of 
congressmen interested in the failure of the economic plan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

