<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Greiff Reportedly Set To Resign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    De Greiff Reportedly Set To Resign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0904011794 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A in Spanish 0002 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0904011794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Seven O'Clock Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Prosecutor General Gustavo de Greiff is disappointed 
with everything and everyone and is very seriously considering 
the possibility of resigning. This is our newscast's 
confidential report. The serious dispute between Prosecutor 
General Gustavo de Greiff and U.S. Government authorities in the 
past days, added to his differences with top officials in 
President Cesar Gaviria's government on all his recent actions, 
has brought up the possibility of his resignation. 
  According to information obtained by this newscast, de 
Greiff 
is seriously considering the possibility of officially tendering 
his resignation next Monday, when he returns from the United 
States. Entirely trustworthy sources have asserted that the 
prosecutor general will resign because he is disappointed with 
what he has called the Colombian Government's lack of solidarity 
in confronting strong criticism by U.S. authorities who accuse 
him of being weak in his negotiations with the drug traffickers. 
  This newscast has also established that next week, the 
prosecutor general will also present a long document in which he 
will clarify his actions with legal arguments and point out that 
all his measures have been in accord with the strict 
implementation of the new criminal law. Prosecutor General de 
Grieff and the Supreme Court chief justice met today to discuss 
the need to strengthen this law. 
  In addition, de Grieff will declare that the Prosecutor 
General's Office is being hindered in continuing the 
investigation of the attack on the Avianca plane and will ask 
the government to appoint ad hoc officials to this case, which 
caused his differences with the United States to increase. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

