<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Orders General's Dismissal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Orders General's Dismissal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0904013094 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0904013094 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] At the request of the Attorney General's Office, 
President Cesar Gaviria today ordered the dismissal of General 
Jesus Armando Arias Cabrales, who led the counterattack on the 
Justice Palace [which was taken over by the M-19 in November 
1985]. Defense Minister [Rafael Pardo] sent a letter to the 
attorney general expressing his disagreement with the decision. 
  Defense Minister Pardo established his ministry's position 
on 
the dismissal of Gen. Arias Cabrales. He said he will obey the 
order but disagrees with it. Why? First, he said that Gen. 
Arias Cabrales only fulfilled a legal duty and carried out a 
legitimate order from his superiors. Pardo insists that the top 
commanders were fully aware of the operation and could have 
stopped it. 
  Second, says Pardo, Gen. Arias Cabrales' responsibility in 
the case is not entirely clear because the criminal 
investigation has not been concluded that an inquiry ordered by 
the prosecutor appointed by the Attorney General's Office is 
still pending. 
  The "National Newscast" has learned that the purpose of this 
inquiry is to find out who gave Gen. Arias Cabrales his orders, 
who was in the chain of command, and who planned the attack on 
the bathroom where several hostages died. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

