<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prosecutor General's Office on Letter on Munoz </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prosecutor General's Office on Letter on Munoz </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0704192794 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0704192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The Prosecutor General's Office has just issued a 
communique explaining why Prosecutor General de Greiff has sent 
the judge who is investigating Dandeny Munoz Mosquera, alias La 
Quica, a letter stating there are no charges against him in the 
case of the Avianca plane. 
  The communique states that the letter has been 
misinterpreted 
and specifies that all de Greiff did was send the information, 
which was requested by La Quica's defense attorney, to the 
United States. Second, the communique notes that by 
constitutional mandate, the Prosecutor General's Office must 
investigate the pros and cons involved in any case. Third, it 
points out that it was the Prosecutor General's Office that sent 
the evidence to the United States that allowed La Quica to be 
condemned in the United States for forgery. 
  De Greiff's controversial letter could change the course of 
La Quica's case, but the judge will not decide until this 
afternoon whether the letter will be accepted. 

</TEXT>

