<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Scores Radio Marti `Political Plots' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paper Scores Radio Marti `Political Plots' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1104150994 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1155 
GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1104150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The weekly newspaper TRABAJADORES today published a 
commentary by reporter Nicanor Leon Cotayo in which he details 
the chaos and ambition prevailing within the anti-Cuban Radio 
Marti. 
  In his commentary, Cotayo says that nine years after its 
creation, this radio station has become a sort of convention of 
chirping crickets hatching political plots. He also mentions the 
tight control exerted on this station by the most reactionary 
Miami circles headed by Jorge Mas Canosa. 
  The article adds that the U.S. Congress this year agreed to 
finance the station with $19 million of the U.S. taxpayers' 
money. But at the same time, it decided to withhold part of 
those funds until an advisory panel reviews Radio Marti 
activities and issues recommendations on the matter. 
  The manipulated objective of this anti-Cuban station is no 
secret to anyone. Moreover, Florida Representative Lincoln 
Diaz-Balart has said this station plays an important role in 
U.S. policy on Cuba. 
  In conclusion, Cotayo states that the validity or lack of 
validity of the role played by the radio station will be 
established by a working group of the U.S. Information Agency, 
but headed by the ultraconservative satellite, Jorge Mas Canosa. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

