<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Figure: Elections Reject Reform </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Figure: Elections Reject Reform </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1104190694 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
0249 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1104190694 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 10 Apr (NA) -- Antonio Bussi, leader 
of the Republican Force, considers the elections for Constituent 
Assembly members "indicate a flat no to the reform, a flat no to 
reelection, and a severe alert to Governor (Ramon) Ortega, as 
the people of Tucuman Province are demanding that he start 
governing." 
  Bussi also indicated that the results of the elections "have 
exploded the dream" of Governor Ortega of being President Carlos 
Menem's number two on the ticket for the 1995 elections. 
  "His balloon has burst," Bussi stressed in remarks to a 
radio 
station. 
  "Please forgive my lack of modesty, but I believe I have 
been 
winning ever since I entered politics because the people of 
Tucuman have no other reasons to forget the recent past, when 
the province had me as governor," he said. 
  Bussi maintained that "as no governor has yet surpassed my 
governorship, the people are thinking about the past," and he 
reiterated that the decision of the voters "is a severe alert to 
Ortega to once and for all start governing the province." 
  The former provincial governor indicated that he has not yet 
studied the possibility of running for the governorship in the 
next elections and stated that the decision will be made by the 
members of the Republican Force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

