<H3> <TI>   Discusses Drug Trafficking </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Drug Trafficking </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1104152594 Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 6 Apr 
94 p 7a </F>

<F P=103> PA1104152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guyanese President Cheddi Jagan expressed concern 
over increased drug trafficking in Guyana and said that he was 
visiting Colombia with a high-raking police official who has 
been entrusted with learning how to fight this scourge. 
  "We are a little scared about the growing threat of drug 
trafficking through Guyana, especially cocaine, which probably 
comes from Colombia through Venezuela," Jagan said today. He is 
on the last day of his visit. 
  Jagan yesterday signed with President Cesar Gaviria a joint 
declaration agreeing to establish an official, private 
binational council to develop various aspects of the 
relationship. 
  The Guyanese president yesterday visited the Cementos del 
Caribe cement factory on the Atlantic Coast and the sugar 
industry in Valle Department. Guyana is interested in both 
products. 

</TEXT>

