<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0804015694 </F>
<F P=103> PY0804015694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 7 April. 
  Brazilian and Chilean Foreign Ministers Celso Amorim and 
Carlos Figueroa signed the "Agreement on Promotion and 
Reciprocal Protection of Investments" at the end of the Rio 
Group meeting held in Rio de Janeiro on 22 March. The agreement 
seeks to create favorable conditions for intensifying bilateral 
economic cooperation, and especially for granting fair and equal 
treatment to investors in the respective countries. (Santiago 
ESTRATEGIA in Spanish 23 Mar 94 p 7) 
  The Chilean trade balance registered a $101.3 million 
surplus 
in February, with exports at $737.2 million and imports at 
$635.9 million. The cumulative surplus for the year's first two 
months was $68.6 million, compared with the same period in 1993 
when there was a deficit of $220.7 million. (Santiago 
ESTRATEGIA in Spanish 24 Mar 94 p 4) 
  The Central Bank reported that the GDP increased 6 percent 
in 
1993, and that the sectors that contributed most to the economic 
growth were construction, with 14 percent; commerce, 
restaurants, and hotels, 8.7 percent; transport and 
communication, 7.9 percent; and financial services, 7.1 percent. 
(Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 24 Mar 94 pp A1, A12) 
  The Consumer Price Index stood at 1.1 percent in March. 
Accrued inflation so far this year stands at 2.5 percent. The 
hike in public utility rates, coupled with an increase in school 
fees, caused the inflation rate to exceed the estimates for the 
first quarter of the year. (Santiago Television Nacional de 
Chile Imagen Internacional in Spanish 0100 GMT 7 Apr 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

