<F P=100> Paraguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Reject Relations With Cuba </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Reject Relations With Cuba </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1104205894 Asuncion ULTIMA HORA in Spanish 11 Apr 94 p 12 </F>
<F P=103> PY1104205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion ULTIMA HORA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Juan Carlos Wasmosy's government 
categorically rejects diplomatic relations with Cuba. Our doors 
will, therefore, remain closed to any initiative in that 
direction. 
  Foreign Minister Luis Maria Ramirez Boettner said this 
morning that our country will not change its position over that 
Caribbean island despite Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto 
Robaina's visit to our country on 15 and 16 April. 
  Following a meeting with the president at government palace, 
Ramirez Boettner said Paraguay is only interested in commercial 
contacts within the framework of Mercosur [Common Market of the 
South]. 
  "Our position continues unchanged. Paraguay has not changed 
its position over Cuba. We will receive him to talk about 
Mercosur and trade matters," said Ramirez Boettner. The foreign 
minister added that Robaina and his entourage will make an 
unofficial visit to the country because we do not have 
diplomatic relations with the island. Ramirez Boettner added 
that Paraguay is very interested in talking about Mercosur, 
particularly because Robaina will be arriving here after 
visiting the other three Mercosur member countries. 
  Ramirez Boettner said he will depart for Marrakech, Morocco, 
tomorrow and will not be in the country during Robaina's visit. 
Robaina will be received by Deputy Foreign Minister Oscar 
Cabello Sarubbi. The foreign minister said Wasmosy will not 
receive the Cuban foreign minister either. "I do not think he 
(Wasmosy) will receive him because his visit is unofficial," the 
foreign minister noted. Robaina wants to talk about Mercosur so 
perhaps he will also meet with Industry and Commerce Minister 
Ubaldo Scavone. 
  An interesting detail is that no government official is 
scheduled to meet Robaina at the airport. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

