<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Costa Rica </F>
<H3> <TI>   President-Elect Emphasizes Integration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President-Elect Emphasizes Integration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0904033694 Paris AFP in Spanish 0956 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0904033694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jorge Araya] </F>
  [Text] San Jose, 7 Apr (AFP) -- According to several 
government officials, following the signing of a free trade 
agreement with Mexico in Mexico City on Tuesday, 5 April, Costa 
Rica's priority is to become part of NAFTA before the rest of 
Central America. 
  Officials in both governments said that after three years of 
negotiations, Mexico and Costa Rica signed the "most advanced" 
commercial treaty in Latin America. The treaty will go into 
effect on 1 January, after it is ratified by both legislatures. 
  Costa Rican President-elect Jose Maria Figueres, a social 
democrat who will assume office on 8 May, noted that trade 
negotiations will be a priority for his administration in an 
effort to put his country on the political map of nations 
advancing toward regional integration. 
  The future president stressed the need to train experienced 
negotiators so they can make the best of the difficult trade 
negotiations ahead, particularly with a view to joining NAFTA, 
formed by Mexico, the United States, and Canada on 1 January. 
  Foreign Trade Minister Roberto Rojas, who has been 
responsible for trade negotiations so far, said that the 
agreement with Mexico puts Costa Rica in a "privileged" position 
for its integration into NAFTA. 
  "We would have liked to have signed a similar agreement with 
the rest of Central America, but that has been more difficult," 
the minister told a group of reporters. He added that before 
such an agreement can be signed, "the right internal, economic, 
and institutional conditions must exist, and Costa Rica found 
them" in the negotiations with Mexico. 
  According to Rojas, it would take approximately 10 years to 
join NAFTA if the negotiations were carried out in concert with 
the other Central American nations, and he predicted that it 
will take two years for Costa Rica to sign a free trade 
agreement with the rest of Central America. 
  The treaty with Mexico gives Costa Rica access to a market 
30 
times larger than the Costa Rican market. Business associations 
and government officials expect a significant boost in foreign 
investment and commercial trade, which currently represents a 
deficit for Costa Rica. 
  In 1993, Costa Rica exported approximately $60 million and 
imported $150 million, mostly in oil purchases, from Mexico. 
  Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani said on Wednesday 
that 
it was "excellent" that Costa Rica had signed the agreement 
because it can serve as an example for the other countries in 
the region, which are currently in preliminary negotiations with 
Mexico. 
  Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras, and Nicaragua form the 
Central America 4 (CA-4) group, which must set a date in the 
next few weeks for the next summit of heads of state to discuss 
the continuation of trade talks with Mexico. 
  These countries agreed on the joint negotiation of a free 
trade agreement with Mexico. Efforts in this direction have 
also been made in Nicaragua, where authorities have expressed 
their desire to sign the agreement this year. 
  The subject was included on President Violeta Chamorro's 
agenda during her official visit to Mexico, which concluded on 
Wednesday. Nicaragua maintains modest trade with Mexico and owes 
that nation nearly $1 billion, half of which is for oil imports. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10407 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat070_e_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-070 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Costa Rica </F>
<H3> <TI>   Businessmen, Workers React to Mexican Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Businessmen, Workers React to Mexican Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0804211594 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2024 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0804211594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 6 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- While Costa Rican 
businessmen and government considered the signing of the Free 
Trade Agreement (TLC) with Mexico a landmark in Costa Rican 
history, union leaders expressed great reservations about this 
economic opening and the consequences it will have for the 
country. 
  The signing of the TLC by Presidents Rafael Angel Calderon 
(Costa Rica) and Carlos Salinas de Gortari (Mexico) in Mexico 
City yesterday, Tuesday, was given wide coverage by the Costa 
Rican media. A television station even broadcast the event live. 
  Costa Rican businessmen and government officials estimate 
that with the TLC, which has to be ratified by the parliaments 
in both countries, exports to Mexico should go from $60 million 
to $250 million in the next five years. This would make Mexico 
Costa Rica's fourth commercial partner, after the United States, 
the European Union, and Central America. 
  In its editorial today, LA NACION newspaper pointed out that 
the signing of the TLC, considered to be one of the most 
advanced of the ones signed in Latin America, "gives a greater 
momentum to a new era of commercial opening," whose commercial 
benefits "are as great as the challenges it poses." After 
highlighting the benefits the TLC can bring to the country, 
offering a market of more than 85 million people to the Costa 
Rican producers, the newspaper warned, however, that "one cannot 
rest on one's laurels because the challenges imposed by this new 
reality are many." "More than ever before, it is necessary to 
expand the economic modernization program," the newspaper 
appraised. LA NACION published a big photograph of Calderon and 
Salinas signing the agreement in its front page, two pages with 
information related to the TLC, and one with the Costa Rican 
president's speech. 
  The LA REPUBLICA newspaper, for its part, gave less coverage 
to this story and published a small photo of Calderon and 
Salinas de Gortari in its first page and highlighted that the 
signing of the TLC opens a ""new era in the relations between 
Costa Rica and Mexico." Costa Rican business sectors are 
focusing on the possibility of developing joint investments, 
starting next January, when the TLC, which will regulate the 
trade in approximately 12,000 products, will go into effect. 
  Carlos Alvarado, the Costa Rican Chamber of Commerce 
president, announced that this same week, Costa Rican 
businessmen will start to make contacts in order to attract 
financial investments. 
  Chamber of Industries President Samuel Yankelewitz said the 
TLC "includes all the elements for things to go well" and 
considered it was "just and balanced" for both nations. 
  Doris Osterlof, the executive director of the Export 
Chamber, 
asserted: "Our industry is prepared" to compete with the 
Mexicans. 
  However, Albino Vargas, secretary general of the National 
Association of Public Employees (ANEP,) questioned the Treaty 
because the labor sector had not participated in the three years 
of negotiations and also because the TLC does not state clearly 
the workers' benefits. 
  Another union leader, Guillermo Garcia, told ACAN-EFE the 
TLC 
will benefit the country's development but said unions had 
reservations about the new economic model (the commercial 
opening) and the consequences it can have. 
  Garcia added that the Costa Rican Government will have to 
abrogate protection measures for workers and labor organizations 
because of the pressures the economic opening will have on Costa 
Rican society. 
  The experience of the decades between the 1960's and the 
1980's, Garcia underscored, left a negative balance because "we 
were asked for sacrifice in exchange for future economic bonanza 
and the economic models that were implemented prompted a larger 
social gap and an unfair distribution of the benefits resulting 
from production." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

