<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Ministry Following Numbers Game Scandal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Ministry Following Numbers Game Scandal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0804185194 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 7 
Apr 94 p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0804185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Army Ministry has been following the charges 
being made about the involvement of police and members of the 
judicial and legislative branches in the numbers game scandal. 
The ministry does not dismiss the possibility of intervention in 
Rio de Janeiro if the state government requests, and the 
president of the Republic so determines. General Gilberto Serra, 
who is Army Minister Zenildo Lucena's spokesman, said: "We are 
following the situation, as our constitutional duties tell us 
to." The Army leadership believes the possibility of an Armed 
Forces' initiative would not have the explicit characteristics 
of an intervention, but of assistance. 
  Chamber of Deputies President Inocencio Oliveira admitted 
the 
possibility of creating a numbers game Congressional 
Investigating Committee to look into charges being made against 
deputies. In Congress, the legislators did not hide their fear 
that the scandal will affect the institution. In Rio de Janeiro, 
Deputy Jorge Bittar -- Workers Party leader in the Chamber of 
Deputies -- announced that he will ask for Mayor Cesar Maia's 
impeachment [preceding word in English]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

